{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630576"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:17:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:17:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17320"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17320"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.67,0.1,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10010"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70058"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10010"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55520"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10021"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23452"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23458"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23508"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70058"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin is a key metabolite formed from the breakdown of haemorrhage. Within the hepatocyte bilirubin is conjugated.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this process?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Addition of amino acids by aminotransferase","Addition of sulphate by sulphotransferase","Addition of glucuronic acid by UDP-glucuronosyltransferase","Reduction by biliverdin reductase","Binding to albumin by protein conjugation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct process is the \u003Cstrong\u003Eaddition of glucuronic acid by UDP-glucuronosyltransferase\u003C/strong\u003E. This enzymatic reaction occurs in hepatocytes and converts fat-soluble unconjugated bilirubin into water-soluble conjugated bilirubin, enabling its excretion in bile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddition of amino acids by aminotransferase\u003C/strong\u003E - Aminotransferases transfer amino groups between amino acids and are not involved in bilirubin metabolism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddition of sulphate by sulphotransferase\u003C/strong\u003E - While sulphation is an important conjugation reaction for steroid hormones and some drugs, it is not the primary mechanism for bilirubin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinding to albumin by protein conjugation\u003C/strong\u003E - Albumin binding occurs with unconjugated bilirubin in blood transport, not during hepatic conjugation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduction by biliverdin reductase\u003C/strong\u003E - This enzyme converts biliverdin to unconjugated bilirubin earlier in the haem breakdown pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe conjugation of bilirubin is essential for normal bile formation and excretion. Deficiency of UDP-glucuronosyltransferase results in conditions such as Crigler-Najjar syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Conjugated bilirubin is formed in hepatocytes through the addition of glucuronic acid to unconjugated bilirubin.","The enzyme UDP-glucuronosyltransferase is responsible for bilirubin conjugation in hepatocytes.","Conjugation makes bilirubin water-soluble, allowing its excretion in bile."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Asbury, C., Rieke, F., Hille, B., Bothwell, M., \u0026 Tuthill, J. (2023) Physiology. Simple Book Publishing. https://uw.pressbooks.pub/physiology/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55520"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17320"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55520"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T09:25:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T09:26:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10010"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70058"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":